<HEADLINE> China Breeds Eight Giant Pandas in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China has successfully bred
eight giant pandas in 1998, according to the China Giant Panda
Breeding Technology Committee.
</P>
<P>
Director Zhang Anju of the committee called it a great
achievement and a great step forward in the mankind's scientific
progress and protection of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said today that only less than 10 percent of the male
giant pandas and 24 percent of female ones in captivity can
naturally have babies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are only 107 giant pandas in the
world's 12 zoos and one protection zone. Up to now, only more than
40 artificially-bred giant pandas have survived.
</P>
<P>
There are some 1,000 giant pandas in the world, mainly living
in the mountains in the juncture of provinces of Sichuan, Gansu
and Shaanxi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
