<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes U.N. Resolutions on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Wednesday hailed the
two resolutions on Cyprus adopted unanimously by the U.N. Security
Council, saying that the U.N. move showed the international
community's strong interest in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The simultaneous adoption of the two resolutions showed both
the strong interest of the international community in the Cyprus
problem and the Security Council's realization of the dangers
entailed by any further prolongation of the problem, Greece's
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said while commenting on the
two resolutions adopted by the U.N. Security Council on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first resolution allows the renewal of the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Cyprus for another six months while the
second calling on the Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots to
respond positively to efforts by U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan's deputy special representative for Cyprus, Ann Hercus, to
secure agreement on measures to reduce tension and build
confidence between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said that it was indeed the first time that the
Security Council, with new, very strong expressions and specific
instructions and directions, appeared determined to make efforts
not only for a short-term reduction of tension, but to tackle in
substance the crucial problem of security and at the same time
moved decisively to resolve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He added that the resolutions clearly described the main
parameters for resolving the Cyprus problem and in so doing,
stated in the most responsible, official and categorical way that
any other proposals raised by the Turkish side were not being
considered by the international community and were regarded as
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that there was only one state and only
one legitimate government in Cyprus and the only solution to the
Cyprus problem was a federation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
For years, the U.N.-sponsored negotiations between the two
communities for peacefully resolving the Cyprus problem have made
no progress due to the differences of their stances towards
settling the division problem.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the situation in the divided island has remained
tense since Cyprus decided last year to purchase and install the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, with Turkey openly
threatening to use force to prevent the missile deployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
