the U.S. and Britain air raids, which lasted four days with a
declared aim to retaliate Iraq's defiance of U.N. weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
The weapons inspections, which began in 1991 after the Gulf War
sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, have repeatedly run
into problems due to the disputes between Baghdad and the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
About 240 U.N. humanitarian staff are now working in northern
Iraq's three Kurdish autonomous governorates. They stayed there
during the bombing and continued their mission.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Officials here warned that damage caused by the air
strikes will make the U.N. humanitarian work in Iraq even tougher.
</P>
<P>
